The '''AGM-183 ARRW''' ("Air-Launched Rapid Response Weapon") is a [[hypersonic weapons|hypersonic]] [[Air-launched ballistic missile|air-to-ground ballistic missile]] planned for use by the [[United States Air Force]]. Developed by [[Lockheed Martin]], the [[boost-glide]] vehicle is propelled to a maximum speed of more than [[Mach number|Mach]] 5<ref>{{cite web |title=AGM-183 ARRW |url=https://www.airforcemag.com/weapons-platforms/agm-183-arrw/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230512023146/https://www.airandspaceforces.com/weapons-platforms/agm-183-arrw/ |archive-date=12 May 2023 |access-date=17 May 2022 |website=Air & Space Forces Magazine}}</ref> by a rocket motor before [[Gliding flight|gliding]] toward its target.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Rogoway |first=Tyler |date=9 August 2020 |title=Check Out This B-52 Stratofortress Carrying Two AGM-183 Hypersonic Test Missiles |url=https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/35530/check-out-this-b-52-stratofortress-carrying-two-agm-183-hypersonic-test-missiles |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200809110051/https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/35530/check-out-this-b-52-stratofortress-carrying-two-agm-183-hypersonic-test-missiles |archive-date=9 August 2020 |access-date=11 October 2020 |website=The Drive}}</ref><ref name="s3.documentcloud.org"/> The program was initially cancelled in March 2023 after multiple failed tests<ref name="2023-03-31_DN">{{cite web |last1=Losey |first1=Stephen |title=US Air Force drops Lockheed hypersonic missile after failed tests |url=https://www.defensenews.com/air/2023/03/30/us-air-force-drops-lockheed-hypersonic-missile-after-failed-tests/ |website=Defense News |archive-url=https://archive.today/20230521031407/https://www.defensenews.com/air/2023/03/30/us-air-force-drops-lockheed-hypersonic-missile-after-failed-tests/ |archive-date=21 May 2023 |language=en |date=30 March 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref> and despite multiple announced cancellations and resumptions of development, development has quietly continued and in 2025 the Air Force announced plans to fund ARRW in FY 2026, with the intent to begin procurement.<ref name=":3">{{Cite web |last=Losey |first=Stephen |date=2025-06-09 |title=Air Force may revive shelved ARRW hypersonic program |url=https://www.defensenews.com/air/2025/06/09/air-force-may-revive-shelved-arrw-hypersonic-program/ |access-date=2025-06-21 |website=Defense News |language=en}}</ref> In 2026, the Air Force announced that its FY 27 budget would include funding for an Increment 2 variant of ARRW with undisclosed enhanced capabilities.<ref name=":4">{{Cite web |last=Newdick |first=Thomas |date=2026-04-30 |title=B-1B Seen Carrying ARRW Hypersonic Missile For The First Time |url=https://www.twz.com/air/b-1b-seen-carrying-arrw-hypersonic-missile-for-the-first-time |access-date=2026-04-30 |website=The War Zone |language=en-US}}</ref> Simultaneously, they announced plans for life-extension modifications to the [[Boeing B-52 Stratofortress]] bomber, developing it as a "standoff" strike weapon,<ref name="new_2026_05_06_avweek">Trimble, Steve: [https://aviationweek.com/defense/aircraft-propulsion/new-heavy-bomber-study-appears-us-air-force-spending-plans "New Heavy Bomber Study Appears In U.S. Air Force Spending Plans"] May 6, 2026, ''[[Aviation Week]],'' retrieved May 8, 2026</ref>
fitting it with external pylons capable of carrying up to 6 AGM-183 missiles per aircraft.<ref name="new_2026_05_06_avweek"/>

==History==
===Development and acquisition===
In August 2018, the U.S. Air Force awarded a $480&nbsp;million contract to [[Lockheed Martin]] for the development of an air-launched hypersonic weapon.<ref name="mil">{{cite news |last1=Pawlyk |first1=Oriana |date=18 June 2019 |title=In First, Air Force Flies Hypersonic Missile Prototype on B-52 Bomber |url=https://www.military.com/daily-news/2019/06/18/first-air-force-flies-hypersonic-missile-prototype-b-52-bomber.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230418073913/https://www.military.com/daily-news/2019/06/18/first-air-force-flies-hypersonic-missile-prototype-b-52-bomber.html |archive-date=18 April 2023 |access-date=23 May 2020 |work=[[military.com]]}}</ref> The resulting missile, the AGM-183A ARRW ("Arrow"), underwent an initial captive carry flight test aboard a [[U.S. Air Force]] [[B-52]] in June 2019.<ref name= "mil" />

In February 2020, the [[First presidency of Donald Trump|Trump Administration]] proposed a 23% increase in funding for hypersonic weapons, and the same month, the [[U.S. Air Force]] announced it had decided to move forward with acquisition of the AGM-183A.<ref name="tirpak">{{cite news |last1=Tirpak |first1=John A. |date=2 March 2020 |title=Roper: The ARRW Hypersonic Missile Better Option for USAF |url=https://www.airforcemag.com/arrw-beat-hcsw-because-its-smaller-better-for-usaf/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230608075113/https://www.airandspaceforces.com/arrw-beat-hcsw-because-its-smaller-better-for-usaf/ |archive-date=8 June 2023 |access-date=17 May 2020 |work=Air & Space Forces Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sanger |first1=David E. |date=10 February 2020 |title=Trump Budget Calls for New Nuclear Warheads and 2 Types of Missiles |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/10/us/politics/trump-budget-nuclear-missiles.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230517203854/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/10/us/politics/trump-budget-nuclear-missiles.html |archive-date=17 May 2023 |access-date=17 May 2020 |work=[[New York Times]]}}</ref>

In March 2020, [[Under Secretary of Defense for Research and Engineering]] [[Michael D. Griffin]] stated that the United States was "close at hand" to having a hypersonic boost-glide weapon ready to field.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harper |first1=Jon |date=4 March 2020 |title=Pentagon to Spend Billions Mass-Producing Hypersonic Weapons |url=https://www.nationaldefensemagazine.org/articles/2020/3/4/pentagon-to-spend-billions-mass-producing-hypersonic-weapons |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231005154951/https://www.nationaldefensemagazine.org/articles/2020/3/4/pentagon-to-spend-billions-mass-producing-hypersonic-weapons |archive-date=5 October 2023 |access-date=17 May 2020 |work=National Defense Magazine}}</ref>

In early 2023, the [[Congressional Budget Office]] (CBO) estimated that a production run of 300 ARRWs would have a unit cost of $14.9 million per missile and a program cost of $5.3 billion including platform integration and 20 years of sustainment. For a production run of 100, each unit would cost $18 million with a program cost of $2.2 billion.<ref name="airspacemag1feb23"/>

On March 29, 2023, [[Assistant Secretary of the Air Force for Acquisition, Technology and Logistics]], Andrew Hunter told the House Tactical Air and Land Forces Subcommittee, a committee responsible for providing oversight for military ammunition, acquisition, and aviation programs,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tactical Air and Land Forces (117th Congress) |url=https://armedservices.house.gov/subcommittees/tactical-air-and-land-forces-117th-congress |access-date=2023-04-01 |website=House Armed Services Committee |date=June 9, 2022 |language=en}}</ref> that the AGM-183A program would not proceed, although the ARRW program's last two all-up round test flights would proceed in order to collect data to help with future hypersonic programs.<ref name="2023-03-31_DN" /> In the Fiscal Year 2025 budget, released March 11, 2024, no funding was provided for procurement or further research and development of the AGM-183, at the time seemingly effectively ending the project.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web |last=Losey |first=Stephen |date=2024-03-12 |title=Air Force budget backs Raytheon hypersonic, no Lockheed missile funds |url=https://www.defensenews.com/air/2024/03/12/air-force-budget-backs-raytheon-hypersonic-no-lockheed-missile-funds/ |access-date=2024-05-19 |website=Defense News |language=en}}</ref> The prototype stage of the program was declared completed in 2024.<ref name=":3" />

However, in 2025, the Air Force announced that it intended to revive the shelved AGM-183A hypersonic program and move it into the procurement phase.<ref name=":3" />  Air Force Chief of Staff Gen. [[David W. Allvin|David Allvin]] announced in a June 2025 congressional hearing that the Air Force wants to include funding for both ARRW and the [[Hypersonic Attack Cruise Missile]] (HACM), in the FY 2026 budget, citing the need to catch up to Chinese and Russian hypersonic operational capabilities.<ref name=":3" /> Acquisition funds were procured for the program in the FY 2026 budget, while the FY 2027 budget includes funding for an Increment 2 variant of ARRW with undisclosed enhanced capabilities and plans on doubling production rates for ARRW, with a planned investment of $1.8 billion across the FYDP between both ARRW and HACM.<ref name=":4" /> The FY 27 budget simultaneously procured funding for $342 million to modernize the remaining B-1B fleet, which will carry the ARRW both as a hypersonic test platform and operationally.<ref name=":4" />

===Theorized relation to the "Super-Duper Missile"===
A "Super-Duper {{sic}} Missile" was announced by US President [[Donald Trump]] during a press availability in the [[Oval Office]] on May 15, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pickrell |first=Ryan |date=15 May 2020 |title=Trump says the US is building a 'super-duper missile' that is much faster than anything it has now |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-says-us-building-what-he-calls-super-duper-missile-2020-5 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240106092129/https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-says-us-building-what-he-calls-super-duper-missile-2020-5?r=US&IR=T |archive-date=6 January 2024 |access-date=16 May 2020 |work=[[Business Insider]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Johnson |first1=Marty |date=16 May 2020 |title=Trump touts new 'super-duper' missile that can allegedly travel 17 times faster than current missiles |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/498148-trump-touts-new-super-duper-missile-that-can-allegedly-travel-17 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230406001442/https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/498148-trump-touts-new-super-duper-missile-that-can-allegedly-travel-17/ |archive-date=6 April 2023 |access-date=16 May 2020 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]}}</ref> According to Trump, the weapon is 17 times faster than existing missiles in the United States arsenal; however, Kingston Reif of the [[Arms Control Association]] believes the claim may have been a misstatement.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Choi |first1=David |date=19 May 2020 |title=Trump's boasts about 'super-duper' missiles reflect misunderstanding of what those weapons actually do |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/trumps-super-fast-and-super-duper-missile-confusion-2020-5 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230406012432/https://www.businessinsider.com/trumps-super-fast-and-super-duper-missile-confusion-2020-5 |archive-date=6 April 2023 |access-date=19 May 2020 |work=[[Business Insider]]}}</ref><ref name="cnn">{{cite news |last1=Browne |first1=Ryan |date=16 May 2020 |title=Trump touts new 'super duper' missile but Pentagon won't confirm details |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/05/16/politics/trump-super-duper-missile/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230405013413/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/05/16/politics/trump-super-duper-missile/ |archive-date=5 April 2023 |access-date=16 May 2020 |work=[[CNN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=16 May 2020 |title=Trump says US developing a 'super duper missile' |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/trump-says-us-developing-a-super-duper-missile/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230405105847/https://www.timesofisrael.com/trump-says-us-developing-a-super-duper-missile/ |archive-date=5 April 2023 |access-date=16 May 2020 |work=[[Times of Israel]] |agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> [[PBS]] news correspondent [[Nick Schifrin]] has theorized that the "Super-Duper Missile" is the AGM-183A, as has the ''[[China Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1= Schifrin |first1=Nick |title=For those interested, the aforementioned super duper missile AGM-183 Air-launched Rapid Response Weapon hypersonic |url= https://twitter.com/nickschifrin/status/1261371357880696832 | work = @nickschifrin |publisher= [[Twitter]] |access-date= May 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=18 May 2020 |title=川普：美國將有「超級飛彈」速度超乎想像 |url=https://www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20200518004347-260417?chdtv |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230406001442/https://www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20200518004347-260417?chdtv |archive-date=6 April 2023 |access-date=18 May 2020 |work=[[China Times]] |language=zh}}</ref>

==Design and Performance==
[[File:B1s.jpg|thumb|The B-1B was being considered as a platform for the AGM-183.]]

The AGM-183A had a claimed maximum speed of more than {{convert|15000|mph|km/h Mach}}.<ref name="pm">{{cite news |last1=Mizokami |first1=Kyle |date=9 April 2020 |title=The B-1 Bomber Might Start Slinging Hypersonic Missiles |url=https://www.popularmechanics.com/military/aviation/a32096936/b-1-bomber-hypersonic-missiles/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230331141322/https://www.popularmechanics.com/military/aviation/a32096936/b-1-bomber-hypersonic-missiles/ |archive-date=31 March 2023 |access-date=20 May 2020 |work=[[Popular Mechanics]]}}</ref>{{Disputed inline|Maximum Speed??|for=disagreement between sources|date=April 2024}} <!-- The Mach number is dependent and local tempeature and pressure, this 750mph at STP 650 mph at 30,000 ft. Which regime is this in? -->

The weapon used a boost-glide system, in which it was propelled to hypersonic speed by a rocket on which it was mounted before gliding toward a target.<ref name="tirpak"/> According to Air Force Global Strike Commander General [[Timothy Ray]], the U.S. Air Force was, as of April 2020, considering using the remaining fleet of [[Rockwell B-1 Lancer|B-1B]] bombers as AGM-183A firing platforms, with each aircraft carrying up to 31 hypersonic weapons (between ARRW and [[Hypersonic Air-breathing Weapon Concept|HAWC]])<ref>{{Cite web |last=Tirpak |first=John |date=2020-04-07 |title=AFGSC Eyes Hypersonic Weapons for B-1, Conventional LRSO |url=https://www.airandspaceforces.com/afgsc-eyes-hypersonic-weapons-for-b-1-conventional-lrso/ |access-date=2024-04-10 |website=Air & Space Forces Magazine |language=en-US}}</ref> mounted on the Common Strategic Rotary Launcher and on external pylons.<ref name="usafmag_b1b"/>

===Testing===
A booster flight test of ARRW took place in April 2021 at [[Point Mugu Sea Range]], off the coast of Southern [[California]] but did not launch successfully;<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gertz |first=Bill |date=3 March 2021 |title=Air Force to test hypersonic missile |url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2021/mar/3/air-force-to-test-hypersonic-missile/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230405204343/https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2021/mar/3/air-force-to-test-hypersonic-missile/ |archive-date=5 April 2023 |website=The Washington Times}}</ref> this was the eighth test for ARRW.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hitchens |first=Theresa |date=3 June 2021 |title=B-21 Speeds To IOC; ARRW Test Slated For Next Month: Ray |url=https://breakingdefense.com/2021/06/b-21-speeds-to-ioc-arrw-test-slated-for-next-month-ray/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231113193616/https://breakingdefense.com/2021/06/b-21-speeds-to-ioc-arrw-test-slated-for-next-month-ray/ |archive-date=13 November 2023 |website=Breaking Defense}}</ref>

Another test in May 2021 for the ARRW's avionics, sensors and communications systems, was successful. The test did not use any of the ARRW's systems but instead used a B-52 based system. On a flight to Alaska from Barksdale Air Force Base in Louisiana, the B-52 was able to receive target data from over {{convert|1000|nmi|km}} away.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Dutton |first=Jack |date=13 May 2021 |title=Air Force Bomber Completes Hypersonic Missile Test Amid China, Russia Arms Race |url=https://www.newsweek.com/bomber-completes-hypersonic-missile-test-1591252 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230405205846/https://www.newsweek.com/bomber-completes-hypersonic-missile-test-1591252 |archive-date=5 April 2023 |website=Newsweek}}</ref>

In July 2021, a second flight test at Point Mugu Sea Range, again being dropped from a [[B-52]] bomber, was a failure as the solid rocket motor failed to ignite.<ref>{{Cite web |last=D'Urso |first=Stefano |date=4 August 2021 |title=First Flight Test Of Hypersonic AGM-183A ARRW (Air-launched Rapid Response Weapon) Fails, Again. |url=https://theaviationist.com/2021/08/04/arrw-test-fails-again/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230607131609/https://theaviationist.com/2021/08/04/arrw-test-fails-again/ |archive-date=7 June 2023 |website=The Aviationist}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Insinna |first=Valerie |date=4 August 2021 |title=After latest flight test failure, US Air Force hopes to keep first hypersonic missile on track for production |url=https://www.defensenews.com/air/2021/08/04/after-latest-flight-test-failure-us-air-force-hoping-to-keep-first-hypersonic-missile-on-track-for-production/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20210805152817/https://www.defensenews.com/air/2021/08/04/after-latest-flight-test-failure-us-air-force-hoping-to-keep-first-hypersonic-missile-on-track-for-production/ |archive-date=5 August 2021 |website=Defense News}}</ref> On December 15, 2021, the third flight test failed to launch as well.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Insinna |first=Valerie |date=20 December 2021 |title=Air Force hypersonic weapon runs into trouble after a third failed test |url=https://breakingdefense.com/2021/12/air-force-hypersonic-weapon-runs-into-trouble-after-a-third-failed-test/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230822183750/https://breakingdefense.com/2021/12/air-force-hypersonic-weapon-runs-into-trouble-after-a-third-failed-test/ |archive-date=22 August 2023 |website=Breaking Defense}}</ref> On March 9, 2022, Congress halved funding for ARRW and transferred the balance to ARRW's R&D account to allow for further testing, which puts the procurement contract at risk.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Insinna |first=Valerie |date=9 March 2022 |title=Air Force can't buy its first hypersonic ARRW as planned, following budget cut |url=https://breakingdefense.com/2022/03/air-force-cant-buy-its-first-hypersonic-arrw-as-planned-following-budget-cut/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230418074058/https://breakingdefense.com/2022/03/air-force-cant-buy-its-first-hypersonic-arrw-as-planned-following-budget-cut/ |archive-date=18 April 2023 |website=Breaking Defense}}</ref>

On May 14, 2022, the 419th Flight Test Squadron and the Global Power Bomber Combined Test Force at [[Edwards Air Force Base]] conducted the first successful test of the ARRW off the coast of Southern California. The weapon demonstrated separation from the [[B-52H Stratofortress]]. Its booster ignited and burned for the expected duration, and the weapon was able to achieve speeds greater than {{convert|5|Mach|km/h mi/h}}.<ref name="first_success">{{cite web |date=16 May 2022 |title=Air Force conducts successful hypersonic weapon test |url=https://www.af.mil/News/Article-Display/Article/3033416/air-force-conducts-successful-hypersonic-weapon-test/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230907154813/https://www.af.mil/News/Article-Display/Article/3033416/air-force-conducts-successful-hypersonic-weapon-test/ |archive-date=7 September 2023 |access-date=17 May 2022 |website=[[United States Air Force]]}}</ref>

The USAF conducted another successful test of the missile on July 12, 2022.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Stone |first=Mike |date=13 July 2022 |title=U.S. successfully tests pair of Lockheed hypersonic missiles |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/aerospace-defense/us-successfully-tested-lockheed-hypersonic-missile-this-week-sources-2022-07-13/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220713182536/https://www.reuters.com/business/aerospace-defense/us-successfully-tested-lockheed-hypersonic-missile-this-week-sources-2022-07-13/ |archive-date=13 July 2022 |access-date=13 July 2022 |work=Reuters |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=13 July 2022 |title=Air Force completes another successful hypersonic test |url=https://www.af.mil/News/Article-Display/Article/3092249/air-force-completes-another-successful-hypersonic-test/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231001153620/https://www.af.mil/News/Article-Display/Article/3092249/air-force-completes-another-successful-hypersonic-test/ |archive-date=1 October 2023 |access-date=13 July 2022 |website=Air Force |language=en-US}}</ref>

The USAF completed the first All-Up-Round (AUR) test on December 9, 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Cole |first=Ilka |date=12 December 2022 |title=Air Force conducts first ARRW operational prototype missile test |url=https://www.eglin.af.mil/News/Article-Display/Article/3240613/air-force-conducts-first-arrw-operational-prototype-missile-test/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231223064903/https://www.eglin.af.mil/News/Article-Display/Article/3240613/air-force-conducts-first-arrw-operational-prototype-missile-test/ |archive-date=23 December 2023 |website=Eglin Air Force Base}}</ref> This test included both the booster and hypersonic glide vehicle.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Insinna |first=Valerie |date=12 December 2022 |title=Air Force successfully tests first fully-operational air-launched hypersonic missile |url=https://breakingdefense.com/2022/12/air-force-successfully-tests-first-fully-operational-air-launched-hypersonic-missile/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230503115718/https://breakingdefense.com/2022/12/air-force-successfully-tests-first-fully-operational-air-launched-hypersonic-missile/ |archive-date=3 May 2023 |website=Breaking Defense}}</ref> The USAF [[412th Test Wing]] used a B-52H Stratofortress, at Edwards Air Force Base.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Losey |first=Stephen |date=12 December 2022 |title=Air Force conducts first launch of prototype hypersonic missile |url=https://www.defensenews.com/air/2022/12/12/air-force-conducts-first-operational-launch-of-arrw-hypersonic-missile/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240106095327/https://www.defensenews.com/air/2022/12/12/air-force-conducts-first-operational-launch-of-arrw-hypersonic-missile/ |archive-date=6 January 2024 |website=Defense News}}</ref> Test was deemed a success, test range sensors malfunctioned, preventing the Air Force from fully knowing whether the glide vehicle and warhead performed as intended in the terminal flight phase.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://breakingdefense.com/2024/03/air-force-conducts-final-test-of-arrw-hypersonic-missile-wont-discuss-specific-results/ |title=Air Force conducts final test of ARRW hypersonic missile, won't discuss 'specific' results |date=March 20, 2024 }}</ref>

On March 13, 2023, the United States Air Force conducted a hypersonic test-launch of an operational AGM-183A prototype from a Boeing B-52H Stratofortress by the [[412th Test Wing]] located at Edwards Air Force Base in California.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Losey |first=Stephen |date=24 March 2023 |title=US Air Force conducts hypersonic test, but full results are unclear |url=https://www.defensenews.com/air/2023/03/24/us-air-force-conducts-hypersonic-test-but-full-results-are-unclear/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240106095545/https://www.defensenews.com/air/2023/03/24/us-air-force-conducts-hypersonic-test-but-full-results-are-unclear/ |archive-date=6 January 2024 |website=[[Defense News]]}}</ref> Air Force Secretary Frank Kendall said the test had failed.<ref name="2023-03-31_DN"/>

On August 19, 2023, the Air Force conducted another test of the ARRW, and said it had "gained valuable new insights into the capabilities" of ARRW.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Losey |first1=Stephen |date=21 August 2023 |title=US Air Force fires hypersonic ARRW in first test since March failure |url=https://www.c4isrnet.com/battlefield-tech/space/2023/08/21/us-air-force-fires-arrw-hypersonic-in-first-test-since-march-failure/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231011141341/https://www.c4isrnet.com/battlefield-tech/space/2023/08/21/us-air-force-fires-arrw-hypersonic-in-first-test-since-march-failure/ |archive-date=11 October 2023 |website=C4ISRNet}}</ref>

On October 12, 2023, the Air Force conducted another test of the ARRW, and said it had "gained valuable new insights into the capabilities of this new, cutting-edge technology".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Tirpak |first=John |date=2023-10-17 |title=Air Force Says ARRW Test Provides 'New Insights,' But Offers Few Specifics |url=https://www.airandspaceforces.com/air-force-arrw-test-new-insights-few-specifics/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231111164502/https://www.airandspaceforces.com/air-force-arrw-test-new-insights-few-specifics/ |archive-date=2023-11-11 |access-date=2023-10-18 |website=Air & Space Forces Magazine |language=en-US}}</ref>

On November 15, 2023, Lockheed Martin announced that the program was at a point where the company and its suppliers were ready for low-rate manufacture following breakthroughs in development.<ref name="lockheedmartin.com">{{cite web |date=15 November 2023 |title=Hypersonics: Rocket Science Meets Critical Capability |url=https://www.lockheedmartin.com/en-us/news/features/2023/hypersonics-rocket-science-meets-critical-capability.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240101125145/https://www.lockheedmartin.com/en-us/news/features/2023/hypersonics-rocket-science-meets-critical-capability.html |archive-date=1 January 2024 |access-date=17 November 2023 |website=Lockheed Martin |language=en}}</ref>

On February 28, 2024, [[Andersen Air Force Base]] released pictures of a live AGM-183A carried by a B-52 bomber as part of a training event.<ref>{{Cite web |first1=Joseph |last1=Trevithick |first2=Thomas |last2=Newdick |date=2024-03-01 |title=B-52 Armed With Hypersonic Missile Makes Appearance In Guam |url=https://www.twz.com/air/b-52-armed-with-hypersonic-missile-makes-appearance-in-guam |access-date=2024-03-02 |website=The War Zone |language=en}}</ref>

On March 17, 2024, the USAF conducted its final planned end-to-end test launch of the AGM-183A, successfully launching one out of a B-52 bomber taking off from Andersen Air Force Base.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=Trevithick |first=Joseph |date=2024-03-19 |title=Unprecedented U.S. Hypersonic Weapons Test From Guam Has Occurred |url=https://www.twz.com/air/unprecedented-u-s-hypersonic-weapons-test-from-guam-has-occurred |access-date=2024-03-20 |website=The War Zone |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web |last=Stone |first=Mike |date=March 19, 2024 |title=US Air Force says it conducted successful hypersonic weapon test |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/us/us-air-force-says-it-conducted-successful-hypersonic-weapon-test-2024-03-19/ |access-date=March 19, 2024 |website=Reuters}}</ref> According to a USAF statement issued on 20 March. “The Air Force gained valuable insights into the capabilities of this technology,” the statement added without giving further details, including whether the test was deemed a success.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://euro-sd.com/2024/03/major-news/37221/usaf-makes-last-agm-183a-test/ |title=USAF conducts likely the last test of a hypersonic all-up-round AGM-183A - European Security & Defence |date=March 22, 2024 }}</ref>

